2026-03-17 16:31:05,784 - OrderManager - INFO - Generated 4 signals: [{'contract_month': '202605', 'prediction_type': 'DIRECTIONAL', 'direction': 'BEARISH', 'reason': 'The Permabear argument is more grounded in the data packet because it leans on multiple direct, domestic balance-sheet indicators that connect cleanly to Henry Hub pricing, whereas the Permabull relies more on second-order inferences (global LNG stress must translate into incremental U.S. feedgas demand) while downplaying contradictory domestic signals.\n\nIndependent bearish lines of evidence (different mechanisms):\n1) Storage/draw pattern: Inventory and Agronomist both cite the 38 Bcf withdrawal to 1,848 Bcf, explicitly described as below expectation and well below the 5-year seasonal norm, which is a concrete bearish balance signal entering injection season. Separately, Sentiment/Volatility cite the first net injection (~42 Bcf) and Volatility notes this flips to a surplus vs the five-year average—another independent sign that the market is moving into a looser regime.\n2) Supply: Multiple reports converge on high production (near-record ~110 Bcf/d; Agronomist additionally references record-level framing and EIA’s 2026 production outlook). This is a direct domestic bearish driver, not a narrative proxy.\n3) Demand softness: Macro reports a ~10% week-over-week demand drop tied to warmer weather—seasonal, but it’s the only clearly quantified broad demand swing in the packet and it points down.\n4) Market/derivatives sentiment: Sentiment highlights persistent heavy net shorts and summer put skew (downside concern). While positioning can create squeeze risk, it still corroborates that informed participants are leaning bearish. \n5) Price/trend context as a soft factor: Price is materially below the 200-day SMA and the 5-day trend is sharply negative. Per the framework, this can’t override fundamentals, but here it is consistent with them.\n\nWhy the bull is less grounded:\n- The bull’s core premise is that global LNG tightness (Europe storage at 18%, Hormuz disruption, high Asian spot prices) will force higher U.S. LNG utilization and lift Henry Hub. That link is plausible, but the Macro report itself flags the causal chain as not fully evidenced (limited data on utilization changes/outages; Golden Pass flows may be commissioning and still small). \n- Bullish domestic items (SNG OFOs, strong LNG exports, Waha constraints) are real but partly regional/operational and do not overturn the broader signals of high production plus the market transitioning to injections. The bull also overweights the 17 Bcf below-5yr storage detail, which the Inventory report explicitly characterizes as “within noise” and not a scarcity premium.\n\nHegelian synthesis: the bear fairly acknowledges squeeze/geopolitical tail risks, and the bull is right that LNG/export call provides a floor and can create upside spikes. But to justify a directional bullish stance, the bull needed stronger independent confirmation that geopolitics is translating into sustained incremental U.S. feedgas demand beyond what is already a “known feature” (~20 Bcf/d feedgas floor) and beyond what domestic loosening (injections + high supply) is signaling.\n\nVolatility cost awareness: CVOL is discussed but not as “options are expensive.” Therefore no automatic thesis-strength downgrade applies. Still, the mixture of signals (global bullish vs domestic bearish) and some data staleness in inventory items argues against “PROVEN.” [Consensus ALIGNED (Vote=BEARISH)] [VOL WARNING: Options expensive. Spread costs elevated. Thesis: PLAUSIBLE]', 'regime': 'HIGH_VOLATILITY', 'volatility_sentiment': 'BEARISH', 'confidence': 0.8, 'price': 3.137, 'sma_200': 3.6742000000000004, 'expected_price': 3.137, 'predicted_return': 0.0, 'thesis_strength': 'PLAUSIBLE', 'conviction_multiplier': 1.0, '_cycle_id': 'NG-8b5635a7'}, {'contract_month': '202606', 'prediction_type': 'DIRECTIONAL', 'direction': 'NEUTRAL', 'reason': 'NO TRADE: Dire